[We thank Jackie Cardwell for the information on the said outbreaks which
seem to occur almost simultaneously in 4 separate, distant locations in
England. Their neurological nature, indicating systemic infection, is less
common than the respiratory syndrome caused by EHV-1. EHV-1 is an enzootic
virus in all countries in which large populations of horses are maintained.
In horses under 3 years of age, clinical ER usually takes the form of an
acute, febrile respiratory illness that spreads rapidly through the group
of animals; hence its common name, equine rhinopneumonitis (ER), which is a
List B disease (caused also by EHV-4). By far the greatest clinical threats
to individual breeding, racing, or pleasure horse operations posed by ER
are the potential abortigenic and neurological sequelae of EHV-1
respiratory infection. EHV-1 (and EHV-4) neurological disease may affect
any age or gender of horse, including mares within a group in which
abortion is occurring.
Although the range and severity of neurological signs associated with EHV-1
infection are broad, some form of hindlimb incoordination and weakness is
common to most cases. More severely affected animals may exhibit further
progression to either hindlimb or quadripedal paralysis, accompanied by
sternal or lateral recumbency. Both morbidity and mortality rates in horses
with EHV-1 neurological disease are highly variable from outbreak to
outbreak. Following recovery from ER, horses usually remain latently
infected with the virus for life. More information on ER diagnosis,
prevention, and control is available in the Office International des
Epizooties manual of standards, diagnostic tests and vaccines, 2000,
chapter 2.5.7. <http://www.oie.int/eng/normes/mmanual/A_00075.htm>. Recent
references can be found there as well. - Mod.AS]
